observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the following:
Acting Municipal Accountant to record the purchases and issuance/utilization of goods and supplies in its appropriate accounts in order to reflect the correct balances at year-end;
Inventory Committee to properly maintain inventory records for monitoring and record-keeping purposes, conduct the semestral physical count on inventories, and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor within the period prescribed;

GFPS headed by the GAD Focal Person and all other Department Heads concerned to:

Ensure that all members of the GFPS including elected local officials and department heads undergo capacity building programs on GAD;
Give priority to those PPAs that will address emerging and/or continuing issues and concerns at all times;

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:

Creation of an Appraisal Committee composed of the Municipal Assessor, Engineer, and Treasurer to facilitate the gathering of necessary data and information regarding the acquisition of lots and to appraise the value of the parcels of land owned by the Municipality; 

After appraisal of the parcels of land, the result will be the basis for the Office of the Municipal Accountant in the recording of the same in the books of accounts; 

The Office of the Municipal Accountant to observe Section 63 of PD No. 1445 and Paragraphs 26 and 27 of the Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standards 17 on the proper measurement on the recognition of the parcels of land and make the necessary correcting/adjusting entries; and



GSO and the Municipal Accountant to maintain Property Cards and Real Property Ledger Cards for the parcels of land.

We recommended and the management agreed that the LCE direct the following:
Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of all its properties and prepare and submit the RCPPE for all types of PPE;
The Municipal Accountant and the GSO reconcile their respective PPE records;
The Municipal Accountant and the GSO maintain the required PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards respectively;
Creation of an Appraisal Committee to aid in the conduct of the physical count of all its properties, especially those which were acquired in prior years; and
The Municipality avail of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts as provided under Commission on Audit (COA) Circular No. 2020-006 to finally establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability.

We recommended and the management agreed that the LCE direct the concerned Accountable Officers and Municipal Treasurer to:
Deposit all collections to the authorized government depository banks daily or not later than the next banking day pursuant to PD 1445 and the NGAS Manual;
Record all transactions (Collections and Deposits, Cash Advances and Liquidations, Deposits and Withdrawals) in chronological order, foot the daily cash balance, and reconcile the same with the actual cash on hand;
Prepare RAAF for checks received and issued;
Completely and correctly record all transactions and properly certify reports; and
Prepare and submit the consolidated RCDs to the Accounting Department for recording purposes.

We recommended and the management agreed that the LCE direct the following:
The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to expedite its procurement processes and transactions;
The General Services Office to timely submit all POs to the Office of the Auditor for review i.e., within five working days from the perfection of contract;
The BAC and all requesting officers and end-users to discontinue the practice of delegating its functions and duties to the suppliers; and
All concerned officials and employees to indicate the correct information in procurement documents.

We recommended and the management agreed that the LCE direct the following:
All the concerned Municipal Officials and Employees to cause the immediate liquidation of cash advances in accordance with the rules and regulations and observe the prescribed periods of liquidation for all cash advances; and
The Municipal Accountant to:
Issue within ten days before the expiration of the one calendar month period, specified under Section 22 of Executive Order No. 77 for official local travel, a written reminder under signature of the head of agency or his authorized representative, enjoining the official or employee concerned to render an account of the cash advance received for his/her travel, pursuant to the rules and regulations on the liquidation of cash advances;
Issue demand letters to those accountable officers with outstanding cash advances that are already beyond the liquidation period;
Refrain from granting additional cash advance to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him/her is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made;
Submit to the Office of the Auditor the DVs, supporting documents, and bank statements of those cash advances that are not liquidated up to this date for issuance of audit suspensions/disallowance, if warranted; and
Reconcile as soon as possible the difference between the balance reported in the status report and the amount disclosed in the Notes to the Financial Statements and submit the updated report to the Office of the Auditor.

We recommended and the management agreed that the LCE direct the following:
GFPS headed by the GAD Focal Person and all other Department Heads concerned to:
Ensure that all members of the GFPS including elected local officials and department heads undergo capacity building programs on GAD;
Give priority to those PPAs that will address emerging and/or continuing issues and concerns at all times;
Use the HGDG tool for GAD fund attribution. If the LGU is not trained on the HGDG, it may propose a training program on the HGDG in its GPB for the incoming year and may seek the assistance of a gender analysis specialist/expert in the use of and/or administration of the HGDG;
Seek technical assistance from the DILG on the formulation of LGU GPBs and on the application of the HGDG;
Coordinate and ensure that PPAs implemented are strictly included in the DILG endorsed GPB or enacted LGU budget; and
Avoid charging to GAD fund expenses that do not directly address gender issues.
Acting Municipal Accountant, together with the GFPS, to facilitate the submission of all Disbursement Vouchers and supporting documents relative to GAD PPAs for verification.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the following:

GFPS headed by the GAD Focal Person and all other Department Heads concerned to:

Ensure that all members of the GFPS including elected local officials and department heads undergo capacity building programs on GAD;

Set up appropriate systems and mechanisms to ensure the generation, processing, review, and updating of sex-disaggregated data or GAD database to serve as basis in performance-based and gender-responsive planning and budgeting;

Give priority to those PPAs that will address emerging and/or continuing issues and concerns at all times;

Use the HGDG tool for GAD fund attribution. If the LGU is not trained on the HGDG, it may propose a training program on the HGDG in its GPB for the incoming year and may seek the assistance of a gender analysis specialist/expert in the use of and/or administration of the HGDG;

Seek technical assistance from the DILG on the formulation of LGU GPBs and on the application of the HGDG;

Ensure that PPAs implemented are strictly included in the DILG endorsed GPB or enacted LGU budget;

Properly fill out the GPB and GAD AR in accordance with the guidelines prescribed therefor; and

Avoid charging to GAD fund expenses that do not directly address gender issues.

MPDO to set up and maintain GAD database to serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;
GAD GFPS or TWG to provide technical assistance to the MPDO in ensuring that the GAD Database is operational;

Reconstitution of GAD Committee and Technical Working Group for the GFPS; and

Acting Municipal Accountant to submit all other Disbursement Vouchers and supporting documents relative to GAD PPAs for further verification.

We recommended that the LCE direct the responsible/concerned department heads to do the following (based on the guidelines prescribed by COA Circular No. 2018-002):

1. Secure directly from the GSIS GIF, all insurances or bonds covering properties, contracts, rights of action, and other insurable risks of their respective offices;

2. Prepare the Property Inventory Form (PIF) listing of the insurable properties and other assets, showing their latest appraised values/valuation, appraised date, location, and other information;


3. Extract from the Report on the Physical Count of PPE the data for the PIF pertaining to the insurable assets and interest of the government;

4. Cause the appraisal of the insurable properties and other assets of their respective offices;

5. Submit the consolidated PIF to the Office of the Auditor and the GIF, GSIS, not later than April 30 of each year; 

6. Include in the annual appropriation the amount of premiums for the general insurance covering all insurable assets and other assets and ensure its payment to the GSIS; and

7. Ensure centralized payment of insurance premiums to avoid double payment.

We recommended that the LCE direct:

1. The Municipal Budget Officer to submit as soon as possible the revised computation for Personal Services (PS) limitation with complete details and information; 

2. The Officials and Employees concerned to return, as soon as possible, the incentives/bonuses/allowances received in excess of the PS Cap limitation in order to avoid issuance of audit suspension/disallowances.

OIC-Municipal Treasurer and Acting Municipal Accountant to make necessary actions to enforce collection of the funds due to the government;



Concerned accountable officers to remit all collections on hand and the liquidating officer to deposit the same not later than the next banking day; and


Immediately preceding and the current OIC-Municipal Treasurer to resolve the abnormal balances by reconciling their respective accounts, making necessary adjustments and notifying the OIC-Municipal Accountant accordingly.

Acting Municipal Accountant to immediately revert back to cash and set-up the corresponding liability account/s of the stale checks identified using the guidelines prescribed under Item 4 b and c, Section 83 (b) of the DOF-BLGF Local Operations Manual;



Municipal Treasurer to verify with the AGDB the veracity of the deposits made amounting to ₱30,000.00 which were recorded in the books but not credited by the bank.

If found void, the OIC-Municipal Treasurer shall charge the floating amount to the responsible Accountable Officer who declared such deposit/s.

We recommended that the LCE:

Direct the full implementation of the provisions of RA No. 9003, together with the members of the SWM Board, in order to avoid administrative sanctions stated in Section 50 of the Act;



Eventually require the establishment of a sanitary landfill which is the ultimate requirement in ensuring the protection of the public health and environment of the Municipality as prescribed by RA No. 9003.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:

Creation of an Appraisal Committee composed of the Municipal Assessor, Engineer, and Treasurer to facilitate the gathering of necessary data and information regarding the acquisition of lots and to appraise the value of the parcels of land owned by the Municipality;

After appraisal of the parcels of land, the result will be the basis for the Office of the Municipal Accountant in the recording of the same in the books of accounts;

The Office of the Municipal Accountant to observe Section 63 of PD No. 1445 and Paragraphs 26 and 27 of the Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standards 17 on the proper measurement on the recognition of the parcels of land and make the necessary correcting/adjusting entries; and

GSO and the Municipal Accountant to maintain Property Cards and Real Property Ledger Cards for the parcels of land.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the following:

Inventory Committee to exert more effort in conducting the physical count of all its properties, maintaining property cards thereon, and preparing the reports with sufficient and more accurate information in accordance with COA Circular 92-386;

Creation of an Appraisal Committee to aid in the conduct of the physical count of all its properties, especially those which were acquired in prior years.

Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) and Report of Waste Materials shall be prepared for unserviceable properties and for items that were damaged, respectively.

Technical inspection from the COA Technical Audit Specialist shall be requested for evaluation of the Management’s appraisal.

Also, request for relief from accountability for equipment that were damaged by typhoon Yolanda should be made;

Submission of the RPCPPE to the office of the Auditor upon completion of the physical count and reconciliation with the Office of the Municipal Accountant;

Maintenance of the subsidiary ledger cards for each group of PPEs of the Accounting Unit. The ledger cards shall be kept to record promptly the acquisition, description, custody, estimated useful life, depreciation, impairment loss, disposal and other information about the asset; and

Maintenance of Property Card for PPE by the GSO to account for the receipt and disposition of the same. This is for check and balance.

We recommended that the LCE direct:

All the concerned Municipal Officials and Employees to cause the immediate liquidation of cash advances in accordance with the rules and regulations and observe the prescribed periods of liquidation for all cash advances;

The Municipal Accountant to:

Send within ten (10) days before the expiration of the 30-day period specified under Section 14 of EO 298 for official local travel a written reminder under signature of the head of agency or his authorized representative, enjoining the official or employee concerned to liquidate his/her travel cash advance/s, pursuant to the rules and regulations on the liquidation of cash advance;

Refrain from granting additional cash advance to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance given to him/her is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made; and

Submit status of unliquidated Cash Advances as of June 30, 2021 to the Office of the Auditor together with the demand letters issued and received by the concerned Accountable Officer. This will serve as basis as to what Disbursement Vouchers with outstanding cash advances shall be subjected to audit suspensions/disallowances.

We recommended that the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to:

Include in the GAD Plan and Budget those projects/programs that directly address a gender issue;

Consider the elements of a gender-responsive program or project in the formulation of its GAD Plan and Budget, such as participation of women and men in problem identification, generation/use of sex-disaggregated data and database, gender analysis to identify gender issues, activities match identified gender issues, among others;

Assess the proposed programs/projects at two levels: 1) the design of the project or program, using the original/revised design documents; and 2) at the project/program implementation, management, and monitoring and evaluation (PIMME);

Comply with the recommendations communicated by the PPDO-GAD Unit in order to ensure that the GAD Plan and Budget be endorsed to the DILG Provincial Office;

Attribute the cost of gender mainstreaming in a regular program using the Harmonized GAD Guidelines (HGDG) tools; and

Henceforth, strictly observe the rules and regulations covering all GAD Activities.

We recommended and the Management agreed that:

The General Services Officer to ensure compliance with the requirements set in the Manual of Audit for Fuel Consumption of Government Motor Vehicles and submit the required reports to the Office of the Auditor;

The Office of the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the following are present before payment: Duly approved Requisition Issue Voucher were attached in every trip together with the charge invoice; Duly approved and completely filled out Driver’s Trip Ticket; and other documents required by COA Circular No. 2012-001 and 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

We recommended that the LCE direct the responsible/concerned department heads to do the following (based on the guidelines prescribed by COA Circular No. 2018-002):

1. Secure directly from the GSIS GIF, all insurances or bonds covering properties, contracts, rights of action, and other insurable risks of their respective offices;

2. Prepare the Property Inventory Form (PIF) listing of the insurable properties and other assets, showing their latest appraised values/valuation, appraised date, location, and other information;

3. Extract from the Report on the Physical Count of PPE the data for the PIF pertaining to the insurable assets and interest of the government;

4. Cause the appraisal of the insurable properties and other assets of their respective offices; and

5. Submit the consolidated PIF to the Office of the Auditor and the GIF, GSIS, not later than April 30 of each year;

6. Include in the annual appropriation the amount of premiums for the general insurance covering all insurable assets and other assets and ensure its payment to the GSIS; and

7. Ensure centralized payment of insurance premiums to avoid double payment.

We recommended the following:
The Supply Officer to prepare procedures on the conduct of physical inventory of PPE and present such to the Agency Head for approval;
The Inventory Committee, with the Supply Officer as one of the members, to develop a plan to include a timeline for the physical inventory, who will supervise the count, the personnel to act as counters and checkers, and the sequence of the counting. A set of written instructions shall be prepared to be observed by each person connected with the inventory-taking. For furniture and fixtures, equipment and the like, inventory tags shall be serially pre-numbered and prepared in duplicate with a perforation separating the top and bottom portions of the tag;
The Inventory Committee to physically count all existing PPE and provide complete description. Secure other information such as person accountable, date of purchase, brand, model, serial no., engine no., etc. and determine if unserviceable or not;
Based on the information gathered in procedure no. 3, determine if accounting records and property records were prepared for these PPEs. If there were none, the OIC-Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer shall create PPELC and PC for each PPE as discussed above. PPE without accounting records shall be properly disclosed;
For the current purchases of PPE, the OIC-Municipal Accountant and GSO shall prepare the PPELC and PC, respectively and issue the corresponding Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) to the accountable employee; and
Management to submit the Report on physical inventory as required by regulations.

We recommended that the LCE direct the꞉
OIC-Municipal Accountant to take up immediately all valid reconciling items requiring adjustment in the books of the Municipality;
OIC-Municipal Accountant to verify with the AGDB of the Municipality if the subject of the credit memo is a valid debit to the Cash in Bank-LCCA Account. Effect immediately in the books of accounts any adjustments, if warranted;
OIC-Municipal Accountant to work hand in hand with the OIC-Municipal Treasurer in tracing the records of the transactions relative to the deposit credited by the AGDB of the Municipality to the bank account amounting to P32,000.00. Make the necessary adjustment in the books of accounts;
OIC-Municipal Treasurer to request for snapshot bank statements every time they have transactions with the AGDB of the Municipality to facilitate prompt reconciliation of book and bank balances; and
OIC-Municipal Treasurer to verify the validation of the deposit slip/s of the recorded debits to Cash in Bank-LCCA account amounting to P30,000.00 in the books but were not credited in the bank account.
Send a letter request, with deposit slip/s attached, if available, to the AGDB of the Municipality that the deposit/s be recognized as valid credit/s to the account.
Otherwise, if there were no deposit/s made, the OIC-Municipal Treasurer shall charge the amount to the responsible Accountable Officer who declared such deposit/s.

We recommended that the LCE direct:
The concerned accountable officers to remit all collections on hand and for the liquidating officer to deposit the same not later than the next banking day;
The immediately preceding and the current OIC-Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the entries appearing in the cash books and adjust errors/inaccuracies accordingly;
The persons responsible to pinpoint the Accountable Officers who still have undeposited collections and make necessary actions to collect the said funds that are due to the government.

We recommended that the LCE direct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to:
Demand from the collectors the prompt turnover of collections at the close of each business day;
Request the collectors assigned in the field to remit to the Designated Liquidating Officer the collections at least once a week or as soon as the collections reach P5,000.00;
Remind the Liquidating Officer to:
Make sure that the Accountable Officers observe issuance of pre-numbered official receipts in strict numerical sequence and check that cancelled Accountable Forms are attached in the Report of Collections before submission to the Office of the Municipal Accountant and eventually to the Office of the Auditor for audit;
Double check the correctness of the collections being remitted to avoid under/over remittance and sign the Reports accordingly; and
Deposit intact all collections turned over by the collectors with the authorized depository bank daily or not later than the next banking day.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
MDRRM Officer to only charge expenses in the 70% of the MDRRM Fund that are related/connected to the implementation of the disaster risk reduction and management PPAs and are aligned with the pertinent provisions of RA No. 10121, NDRRM Plan 2011-2018 and rules and regulations pertaining to the utilization of the 5% MDRRM Fund to avoid future audit suspensions and disallowances;
MDRRM Officer to stop the practice of reimbursement since there was a revolving fund set-up solely for the MDRRM Office;
The persons accountable/responsible for the revolving fund to not allow the charges of repairs, fuel, office and other supplies expenses out of the cash advance.
Persons responsible to attach complete and proper supporting documents to each and every claim for easy evaluation of the correctness and propriety of the same;
OIC-Municipal Accountant to double check completeness and propriety of supporting documents before payment; and
Municipal Engineer, as the one approving the trip tickets, to properly monitor fuel purchases and usage for each official vehicle in accordance with the Manual on Fuel Consumption.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
Chairperson of the Gender and Development (GAD) Focal Point System and all the concerned members to be mindful of the gender issue or gender mandate of the Municipality and carefully identify the activities if the same can address either the client-focused or organization-focused gender issue prior to its inclusion in the GAD Plan and Budget;
Concerned personnel to use appropriate Harmonized Gender and Development Guidelines (HGDG) tools in the attribution or mainstreaming of the Municipality’s program/projects/activities (PPAs) in the GAD Plan and Budget such as design checklist (HGDG Boxes 9-15, 18-23), the funding facilities checklist (HGDG Box F1) or the generic checklist (HGDG Box 7a). For its Accomplishment Report, the Municipality can use the Project Implementation and Management, and Monitoring and Evaluation (PIMME) checklist (HGDG Boxes 16 and 17) or the Facility Implementation, Management, and Monitoring and Evaluation (FIMME) checklist (HGDG Box F2).

We recommend that the LCE direct:
The concerned Department Heads to include the projects, under the ADM Program, in the APP of the ensuing year considering that the projects are still ongoing;
The persons responsible to re-assess the project schedule/timeline and the actual implementation of the project and impose liquidated damages, if warranted;
The persons responsible to attach the complete bidding documents to facilitate the timely audit of disbursements; and
The Engineering Department to attach related pictures before, during and after the construction, detailed drawings/plans and specifications and other necessary documents. The said documents will be used by the Audit Team in conducting inspection of the implemented projects.

The Inventory Committee to physically count all existing PPE and provide complete description. Secure other information such as person accountable, date of purchase, brand, model, serial no., engine no., etc. and determine if unserviceable or not;

Based on the information gathered in procedure no. 3, determine if accounting records and property records were prepared for these PPEs. If there were none, the Municipal Accountant and GSO shall create PPELC and PC for each PPE as discussed above. PPE without accounting records shall be properly disclosed;

For the current purchases of PPE, the Municipal Accountant and GSO shall prepare the PPELC and PC, respectively and issue the corresponding Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) to the accountable employee;
